---
import DocsLayout from "@/layouts/docs.astro"
import { Code } from "astro:components"
---

<DocsLayout title="Getting Started" description="Install and use instant-grep in minutes">

  <h1>Getting Started</h1>
  <p>
    From zero to sub-millisecond search in under 5 minutes. No configuration files.
    No daemons to set up manually. Just build and go.
  </p>

  <div class="docs-callout">
    <div>
      <p><strong>New in v1.10.0:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><code>ig --top N "pattern"</code> — BM25 ranking returns the N most relevant files instead of the first N found on disk. See <a href="/docs/cli#bm25">CLI reference</a>.</li>
        <li><code>ig --semantic "error"</code> — PMI-learned query expansion (no ML model, synonyms learned from your repo during indexing). See <a href="/docs/cli#semantic">CLI reference</a>.</li>
        <li>Auto-compact output when piped to an agent + dir-aggregate <code>ig smart &lt;dir&gt;</code> and <code>ig files</code>. See <a href="/docs/vs-rtk">vs rtk bench</a>: ig now beats rtk on total bytes and total wall time.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Rust toolchain (stable) — <code>rustup toolchain install stable</code></li>
    <li>Cargo (comes with Rust)</li>
    <li>A terminal and a project to search through</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Installation</h2>
  <p>
    The fastest way to install ig is via the one-line installer. It downloads the latest release binary and auto-configures your AI agents.
  </p>

  <Code
    code={`# Install latest release + auto-configure AI agents
curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/MakFly/instant-grep/main/install.sh | bash`}
    lang="bash"
    theme="github-dark"
  />

  <p>Or via Homebrew:</p>

  <Code code="brew install MakFly/tap/ig" lang="bash" theme="github-dark" />

  <p>Or build from source:</p>

  <Code
    code={`# Clone and build
git clone https://github.com/MakFly/instant-grep
cd instant-grep
cargo build --release

# Copy to PATH
cp target/release/ig ~/.local/bin/ig

# Verify
ig --version`}
    lang="bash"
    theme="github-dark"
  />

  <div class="docs-callout">
    <div>
      <p><strong>Tip:</strong> Make sure <code>~/.local/bin</code> is in your <code>$PATH</code>.
      Add <code>export PATH="$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH"</code> to your shell config if needed.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Configure AI agents</h3>
  <p>
    If you used the one-line installer, agents are already configured. Otherwise run:
  </p>

  <Code
    code={`# Auto-configure Claude Code, Codex, Gemini CLI...
ig setup

# ig setup does the following:
#  - Installs ig-rewrite.sh hook in ~/.claude/hooks/
#  - Registers the hook in ~/.claude/settings.json
#  - Adds Bash(ig *) permission for Claude Code
#  - Adds search tools section to ~/.claude/CLAUDE.md`}
    lang="bash"
    theme="github-dark"
  />

  <h2>Build your first index</h2>
  <p>
    Navigate to any project directory and run <code>ig index</code>.
    This creates a <code>.ig/</code> directory with binary index files
    and auto-generated project artifacts.
  </p>

  <Code
    code={`$ ig index .

* Scanning directory tree
* Skipping 38 excluded directories (node_modules, target, .git, ...)
* Building sparse n-gram index: 1,552 files (SPIMI, 2 segments)
+ Index built in 450ms
   lexicon:  31 MB   (.ig/lexicon.bin)
   postings: 7.1 MB  (.ig/postings.bin)
   metadata: 111 KB  (.ig/metadata.bin)`}
    lang="bash"
    theme="github-dark"
  />

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-3 gap-3 my-6">
    <div class="p-4 rounded-lg border text-center">
      <div class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold mb-1">lexicon.bin</div>
      <div class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">Hash table mapping n-grams to posting list offsets</div>
    </div>
    <div class="p-4 rounded-lg border text-center">
      <div class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold mb-1">postings.bin</div>
      <div class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">VByte delta-encoded file ID lists per n-gram</div>
    </div>
    <div class="p-4 rounded-lg border text-center">
      <div class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold mb-1">metadata.bin</div>
      <div class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">File paths, modification times, version info</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Your first search</h2>
  <p>
    Run <code>ig</code> with any regex pattern. If no index exists, it builds one automatically.
  </p>

  <div class="docs-callout">
    <div>
      <p><strong>Shortcut:</strong> <code>ig "pattern"</code> is equivalent to <code>ig search "pattern"</code>.
      The <code>search</code> subcommand is optional.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <Code
    code={`# Basic search
ig "async fn" src/

# Case-insensitive search
ig -i "TODO" .

# With context lines
ig -C 3 "Result<T>" .

# JSON output for AI agents
ig --json "impl Trait" .

# Filter by file type
ig --type rs "pub fn" .`}
    lang="bash"
    theme="github-dark"
  />

  <h2>How auto-build works</h2>
  <p>
    When you run <code>ig search</code>, it checks if a <code>.ig/</code> index
    exists in the target directory. If not, it automatically runs <code>ig index</code> first.
    You can always just run search — no manual indexing required.
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li><code>ig "pattern" .</code> called</li>
    <li>Check for <code>.ig/metadata.bin</code> — if missing, build index first</li>
    <li>Extract n-grams from regex, query posting lists, verify matches</li>
    <li>Results printed in ~0.9ms</li>
  </ol>

